[## LECTURE 5.1 — CONTAINER SCANNING: TRIVY IN CI/CD PIPELINE]

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your application is secure. Your database is encrypted.
Your logs are immutable. But what about the container image
you just pushed to production?

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Does it contain a vulnerability from six months ago
that someone forgot to patch? That is the problem
with supply chain security.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Your base image has vulnerabilities.
Your Python dependencies have vulnerabilities.
Even your distroless image has vulnerabilities in the kernel.

4
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
For SOC 2, you need to find and fix these
before they reach production.
Hi there, and welcome to Phase 5 of our SOC 2 journey.

5
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
In this phase, we are building a complete
vulnerability management program in CI/CD.
Container scanning, dependency scanning, secret detection.

6
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
SBOM generation, CVE SLAs, image signing,
and policy as code. By the end of these two hours,
every container image you deploy will be scanned,
signed, and verified before it ever touches production.

7
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Let me start with the most critical tool.
Trivy for container scanning.
Trivy is an open-source vulnerability scanner.

8
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
It checks OS packages and language dependencies.
It is fast, accurate, and integrates directly into GitHub Actions.

9
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
First, configure Trivy with a dot trivy dot yaml file.
Set severity to CRITICAL, HIGH, and MEDIUM.
MEDIUM only warns, does not fail the build.

10
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Set ignore-unfixed to false.
Report vulnerabilities even if no fix is available yet.
Set vulnerability type to os and library.

11
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Skip directories like dot git, dot venv, tests.
Skip files like dot env example and docker-compose files.
Set format to table and exit-code to one.

12
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Exit-code one means fail the CI on any CRITICAL or HIGH finding.
Create a dot trivyignore file for false positives.

13
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Now integrate Trivy into GitHub Actions.
Create a workflow file called ci dot yml.
Trigger on pull requests to main and develop.

14
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Also trigger on push to main and on a daily schedule.
The daily schedule catches vulnerabilities in dependencies
that were already merged.

15
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
In the security-scan job, first build the Docker image.
Then run a filesystem scan with Trivy.
Scan the entire codebase including the Dockerfile.

16
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
Then run an image scan on the built container.
Both scans output SARIF format.
This format is supported by GitHub's security tab.

17
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Upload both SARIF files to GitHub using the CodeQL action.
Now vulnerabilities appear directly in the GitHub Security tab.
Developers see them without leaving the pull request.

18
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
What happens when a vulnerability is found?
The CI pipeline fails with clear output.
A table shows the library, vulnerability ID, severity,
installed version, and fixed version.

19
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
For false positives or unavoidable vulnerabilities,
add them to dot trivyignore with a comment.
Explain why each ignored vulnerability is acceptable.

20
00:09:30,000 --> 00:10:00,000
Now set up a weekly scheduled scan.
Run every Monday at 6 AM.
Scan with severity CRITICAL, HIGH, and MEDIUM.

21
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:30,000
Convert the SARIF to Security Hub format and import.
Create GitHub issues for any new critical findings.
The issue includes the vulnerability ID, severity,
package, fixed version, and description.

22
00:10:30,000 --> 00:11:00,000
Your lab exercise is to run Trivy on your Docker image.
Identify any CRITICAL or HIGH vulnerabilities.
For each vulnerability, determine if it is a false positive
or needs remediation.

23
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:30,000
Create a dot trivyignore file for any false positives.
Document your vulnerability remediation SLA.
In the next lecture, we will scan Python dependencies.

