[## LECTURE 5.3 — SECRET DETECTION: GITLEAKS AND TRUFFLEHOG]

41
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Vulnerabilities are one thing.
Hardcoded secrets are another.
And they are arguably more dangerous.

42
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
An API key in a commit is immediately compromised.
You need to prevent secrets from ever entering your repository.
Let me show you Gitleaks.

43
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Gitleaks scans for secrets in Git history.
Add it to your pre-commit configuration.
Rev v8.18.4 is stable.

44
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Also add TruffleHog for additional coverage.
TruffleHog verifies secrets by attempting to use them.
It has a lower false positive rate.

45
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Now configure custom rules for your specific secrets.
Create a dot gitleaks dot toml file.

46
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
First rule. OpenAI API keys.
The regex looks for sk dash followed by 48 alphanumeric characters.
Tags include key, openai, llm, critical.

47
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Second rule. Groq API keys.
The regex looks for gsk underscore followed by 48 alphanumeric characters.
Third rule. AWS Access Keys. AKIA followed by 16 uppercase letters or digits.

48
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Fourth rule. Vault Tokens.
hvs dot followed by alphanumeric and underscore dash characters.
Fifth rule. JWT Tokens.
The standard JWT regex with three base64 sections separated by dots.

49
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Sixth rule. Database connection strings.
PostgreSQL URLs with username, password, and host.
The allowlist section excludes false positives.

50
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Exclude dot env example files.
Exclude the dot gitleaks dot toml file itself.
Exclude dot pre-commit-config dot yaml.
Exclude test fixtures.

51
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Now run secret scanning in CI.
This catches anything that bypasses the pre-commit hook.
Checkout with fetch-depth zero for full history.

52
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Run Gitleaks with your configuration file.
Output SARIF format.
Run TruffleHog in a Docker container.

53
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
TruffleHog scans the filesystem with the only-verified flag.
This means it actually tests the secrets, reducing false positives.
Upload the Gitleaks SARIF to GitHub.

54
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
If the scan fails, run a revocation script.
Parse the findings and revoke any exposed secrets.
Call the OpenAI API to revoke a leaked key.

55
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:30,000
For AWS keys, call iam dot delete_access_key.
For Vault tokens, call the Vault API to revoke.
What happens when a secret is found in a commit?

56
00:07:30,000 --> 00:08:00,000
The pre-commit hook blocks the commit.
Gitleaks prints the finding, the secret, the rule, the file, and the commit.
The output says commit blocked. Remove secret and use Vault instead.

57
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:30,000
To bypass, not recommended, you can set SKIP equals gitleaks.
But that defeats the purpose.
Your lab exercise is to add a fake secret to a file.

58
00:08:30,000 --> 00:09:00,000
Verify the pre-commit hook blocks it.
Then remove the secret and commit successfully.
Document your secret revocation process.

59
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:30,000
In the next lecture, we will generate a Software Bill of Materials.
An SBOM for every container image.

