[## LECTURE 5.4 — SBOM GENERATION: SOFTWARE BILL OF MATERIALS]

60
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Your auditor will ask. What is in your container?
What dependencies are you shipping?
You need a Software Bill of Materials.

61
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
A complete inventory of every package, library,
and component in your application.
SBOMs are becoming mandatory for government contracts
and enterprise customers.

62
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Syft from Anchore generates SBOMs in multiple formats.
Add an SBOM generation job to your CI workflow.

63
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
First, build the Docker image.
Then generate an SBOM with Syft in SPDX JSON format.
SPDX is the Linux Foundation's standard.

64
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Also generate a CycloneDX format SBOM.
CycloneDX is preferred by many security tools.
Upload both SBOMs as build artifacts.

65
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Attest the SBOM to GitHub using gh attestation.
This proves the SBOM matches the image.
Then upload the SBOM to Dependency Track.

66
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Dependency Track is an open-source component analysis platform.
It tracks vulnerabilities across your SBOM over time.
Use an API key for authentication.

67
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Here is what an SBOM looks like in SPDX format.
It has an SPDXID and a name.
Creation info includes the creation time and the tool that generated it.

68
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Then a list of packages.
Each package has a name, version info, download location,
license declared, and copyright text.

69
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
External references include CPE identifiers and package URLs.
Relationships show which packages are contained in the document.
This is a complete inventory.

70
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Now verify the SBOM matches what is actually running.
Generate an SBOM from the running container.
Then compare it with the committed SBOM using diff.

71
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Also verify the SBOM signature with Cosign.
cosign verify-attestation with the public key.
Your lab exercise is to generate an SBOM for your container image.

72
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
In SPDX and CycloneDX formats.
Upload it to Dependency Track or a similar platform.
Verify that the SBOM includes all your Python dependencies
and base OS packages.

73
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
In the next lecture, we will define CVE SLAs.
