[## LECTURE 5.6 — IMAGE SIGNING: COSIGN AND NOTATION]

90
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You have scanned your image. No vulnerabilities.
But how do you know the image running in production
is the same one you scanned?

91
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
What if someone tampered with it in the registry?
Image signing cryptographically verifies that an image
came from your CI pipeline and has not been modified.

92
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Let me show you Cosign from Sigstore.
First, generate a key pair.
cosign generate-key-pair.

93
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
This creates two files. cosign dot key, the private key.
And cosign dot pub, the public key.
Store the private key in Vault. Never in Git.
Store the public key in Git. It is safe to share.

94
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Now sign your image in CI.
In the build-and-sign job, first build the Docker image.
Push it to the registry with the commit SHA as a tag.

95
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Install Cosign using the sigstore action.
Then sign the image with the private key.
Set the password and private key from GitHub secrets.

96
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Finally, verify the signature immediately after signing.
This proves the signature is valid before proceeding.

97
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Now enforce signature verification in Kubernetes.
Create a ClusterImagePolicy.
Images that match the glob pattern must be signed.

98
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
The authority section includes the static public key.
Also include keyless authority for development environments.
Set mode to enforce. Reject unsigned images.

99
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
In your deployment, add an annotation.
cosign dot sigstore dot dev forward slash verify equals true.
The admission controller checks the signature before allowing the pod.

100
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Verify signatures in production.
Get all pods and extract their image names.
Loop through each image and run cosign verify.

101
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Monitor the admission controller logs.
kubectl logs minus n cosign-system deployment forward slash cosign-webhook.
It logs every verification attempt.

102
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Your lab exercise is to generate a Cosign key pair.
Sign your container image. Push the signed image to a registry.
Verify the signature.

103
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Test what happens when you try to deploy an unsigned image.
The admission controller should reject it.
In the next lecture, we will validate Kubernetes manifests.
With OPA Conftest.

