[## LECTURE 5.7 — POLICY AS CODE: OPA CONFTEST]

104
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:30,000
You have scanned, signed, and verified your images.
But what about the Kubernetes manifests themselves?
Are they configured securely?

105
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
Are they using the right image registry?
Do they have resource limits?
Policy as Code with Open Policy Agent Conftest
lets you validate YAML manifests before deployment.

106
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Write policies in Rego, a declarative query language.
Create a policies directory and a security dot rego file.

107
00:01:30,000 --> 00:02:00,000
First policy. Enforce image registry.
If the kind is Deployment, get the container image.
If the image does not start with your registry, deny it.

108
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:30,000
Second policy. Enforce run as non-root.
If the container does not have securityContext dot runAsNonRoot equals true, deny it.

109
00:02:30,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Third policy. Enforce resource limits.
If the container does not have resources dot limits, deny it.
Without limits, a single container could starve all others.

110
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Fourth policy. Enforce read-only root filesystem.
If the container does not have readOnlyRootFilesystem equals true, deny it.
This prevents attackers from writing to the container's filesystem.

111
00:03:30,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Fifth policy. Prevent NodePort services.
If the service type is NodePort, deny it.
NodePort exposes services on a high port on every node.
Use LoadBalancer or ClusterIP instead.

112
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Sixth policy. Require labels.
If the deployment does not have a label called app, deny it.
Labels are required for monitoring and debugging.

113
00:04:30,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Now run Conftest in CI.
Install Conftest by downloading the binary from GitHub.
Then run helm template to generate the Kubernetes manifests.

114
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:30,000
Pipe the manifests to conftest test.
Point to the policies directory.
Output JSON and check for failures.

115
00:05:30,000 --> 00:06:00,000
If any failures exist, print them and exit with code one.
Test locally. conftest test deployment dot yaml dash dash policy policies.
The output shows which policies failed and why.

116
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Your lab exercise is to write a Rego policy.
Enforce your organization's security standards.
Run Conftest on your Helm templates.

117
00:06:30,000 --> 00:07:00,000
Fix any violations. Document your policy rules.
In the next lecture, we will build a vulnerability dashboard.
With Grafana and Security Hub.

